    <h2>Why it persists.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">Every report is individually rational</span>

    <p>The trap survives because nobody is positioned to see it whole. Each report, examined on its own, is defensible — somebody asked for it, somebody reads it, and "it only takes an hour or two." But nobody multiplies that hour by its weekly frequency, by the number of reports, by the number of people touching them. The aggregate lives in no one's job description, so it goes unmeasured, and what goes unmeasured goes unmanaged.</p>

    <p>There's a budget illusion at work too. Automating a report looks like a cost: a project, maybe a tool, definitely someone's time. Producing it by hand looks free, because the analyst's salary is already committed. So the rational-seeming choice, made fresh every quarter, is to keep doing it by hand — even when twelve months of hand assembly costs several times what the fix would have. The trap is funded by the fact that its costs never arrive as a line item.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <h3>The one-week burden inventory</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>List every recurring report</strong> — dashboard refreshes done by hand count; so do "quick" data pulls that happen every week.</li>
        <li><strong>For each:</strong> who builds it, how often, how many hours per cycle, how many source systems feed it, and who actually reads it.</li>
        <li><strong>Do the arithmetic:</strong> hours per cycle × cycles per month × people involved. Sum it. That monthly number is your burden.</li>
        <li><strong>Mark the fragile ones</strong> — any report only one person knows how to produce gets a flag, regardless of its hours.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Measure it before you fix it.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">The number does the persuading</span>

    <p>The burden inventory above takes most teams a single honest week, and it changes the conversation permanently. "We spend a lot of time on reporting" persuades no one — it sounds like every team's complaint about every kind of work. "We spend two hundred and ten analyst-hours a month assembling forty-one recurring reports, eleven of which have no confirmed reader" is a different sentence. It turns a vague grievance into a managed problem with a size, an owner, and an obvious next question. This is exactly why a manual-burden analysis is one of the ten deliverables in our <a href="/assessment">Reporting Clarity Assessment</a> — not because counting hours is sophisticated, but because nothing downstream moves until the number exists.</p>

    <h2>The fix order: retire, consolidate, automate.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">In that order — and the order is the whole trick</span>

    <p>The instinct is to jump straight to automation, and it's the wrong first move. <strong>Retire first.</strong> The cheapest report to automate is one nobody reads, and every portfolio that's grown by accretion has them — reports that outlived their question, their requester, or both. The inventory's "who actually reads it" column finds them. Sunsetting them costs nothing but a slightly awkward email, and it routinely clears a meaningful share of the burden before anything is built.</p>

    <p><strong>Consolidate second.</strong> Of the reports that survive, several usually answer overlapping questions for different audiences — three versions of the same weekly story, each hand-built separately. Merging them into one well-designed report with clear views cuts assembly again, and as a bonus removes a source of the number conflicts that erode trust. Only then, <strong>automate third</strong> — and only the reports that have earned their place. Automating before retiring and consolidating just cements waste into infrastructure: you pay the project cost to faithfully reproduce reports that shouldn't exist.</p>

    <p>Notice what this sequence is not: a tool purchase. Modernization keeps getting sold as software, but the leverage here is decisions — which reports live, which die, which merge — and decisions are cheap. The technology that automates a justified, consolidated report is usually the easy part, and it's the last part. (This is the same logic as the broader case that <a href="/insights/reporting-not-dashboard-redesign">modernization is not a dashboard redesign</a> — the visible artifact is the last 10% of the problem.)</p>

    <div class="tip">
      <div class="tlabel">Where to start right now</div>
      <p>Pick the single most painful recurring report — the one whose name makes an analyst sigh. Next time it's built, have the builder log every step and the clock time, just once. That one log usually reveals two or three steps that can be eliminated this week, and it gives you the template for the full inventory. If you want a read on how your whole environment scores — manual burden included — the free <a href="/resources/#checklist">Reporting Trust Health Check</a> takes about three minutes, no email required.</p>
